<DOCNO> AP891212-0015 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
worries that foreigners are buying up america 
are unfounded although foreign ownership of us businesses 
increased dramatically in the past decade a washington research 
group says 
subsidiaries of foreign companies generally operate in the same 
manner as usowned companies the institute for international 
economics reported in a study released monday 
the foreign firms generally paid wages comparable to those in 
usowned businesses and invested about the same money in research 
and development in this country according to the study by paul 
krugman an economics professor at the massachusetts institute of 
technology and edwin m graham a business professor at duke 
university 
the study argued that it would be a mistake for congress to 
change us laws in an effort to block foreign investment 
especially given the fact that the united states depends on foreign 
capital flows of 100 billion annually to finance its merchandise 
trade deficits 
i have deplored as loudly as anyone the fact that we are 
having to attract 10 billion a month in foreign investment but 
the money is much more likely to stay put if it comes in as a 
direct investment rather than as foreign investment in the stock 
market or bond market said c fred bergsten a former treasury 
department official and the head of the institute 
the institutes study said foreign firms accounted for 7 percent 
of total us employment in manufacturing in 1986 the most recent 
year for which statistics were available that compared to 21 
percent in france 14 percent in britain and 13 percent in west 
germany 
however the researchers said that while japanese companies are 
investing heavily in the united states foreigncontrolled 
companies account for just 1 percent of manufacturing employment in 
japan a drop from 2 percent in 1977 
the heavy purchases by foreigners in particular the japanese 
have aroused concern in congress and elsewhere that the united 
states is selling its economic destiny to foreigners 
foreign direct investment totaled 89 percent of all 
nonfinancial corporations in the united states in 1988 up from 
21 percent in 1977 according to the commerce department 
rudy oswald chief economist at the aflcio said the institute 
was wrong to conclude that foreign investment is basically a benign 
influence on the us economy 
the united states is losing control of its own economic 
destiny in many ways oswald said it means that investment 
decisions are being made not in terms of what is necessarily good 
for a us firm but what is in the worldwide plan of a foreign 
firm 
the commerce department said foreign direct investment in us 
real estate and businesses totaled 3289 billion in 1988 compared 
with 3269 billion in us ownership overseas that was the first 
year that foreign direct ownership in the united states surpassed 
american investment abroad 
britain has the largest stake in the united states holding 31 
percent of total foreignheld assets while japan climbed to the 
no 2 spot with 162 percent of the total ahead of the 
netherlands which held 149 percent 
purchases of prime real estate and hollywood movie studios by 
the japanese grabbed the headlines but the most dramatic inroads 
by the japanese have come in banking according to the institutes 
study 
it reported that the japanese in 1988 controlled 522 percent of 
the us banking assets held by foreign banks far ahead of the 
second biggest foreign holder canada which controls 71 percent 
in all foreign banks controlled 192 percent of total american 
banking assets in 1988 up from 8 percent a decade earlier 
the institute for international economics is a nonprofit 
research institute created in 1981 it receives funding from the 
german marshall fund of the united states an independent endowment 
created by the west german government and various us 
corporations including the ford foundation 
