hours in the air during the search 
you turn the plane in that direction but you really have no 
idea how far away it is he said you only see the flare 
momentarily almost like if you were in your car and saw 
lightning in the distance 
with every passing hour the odds against finding survivors grew 
slimmer 
you just feel this incredible pressure because youre trying 
constantly to get caught up with the situation because the search 
area grows larger and larger the potential drift areas grow and 
the information going into designing the mission grows stickney 
said 
during the height of the search stickney spent his onduty 
hours absorbed in mathematics and probabilities he and his flight 
crew focused solely on resisting the lull of mile after mile of 
greenishgray sea and preventing their vision from blurring before 
an endless stretch of horizon 
youre right on the edge and you just keep thinking ive got 
to stay alert ive got to concentrate because the next time you 
glance left you could spot a life raft stickney said 
but sometimes the fates conspire against coast guard missions 
turbulent air jostles planes or 20foot seas and windwhipped water 
obscure the view sometimes as was the case with the heidi marie 
what seems a hot trail suddenly turns cold 
the search planes are equipped with hightech radar infrared 
heatdetecting sensors and data marker buoys to track conditions at 
sea but mostly the rescuers rely on their eyes pilots scanning 
from the cockpit and observers peering through 3foot windows 
their backs get sore and their eyes strain against 
lateafternoon shadows and hours of staring into the glare of 
clouds then snow then brilliant blue sky 
because the heidi maries life raft was made of cloth it was 
undetectable on radar because it was so small their field of 
vision was limited to about a mile off either wing 
