<TEXT>
buddhists on tuesday unveiled a stuffed 
version of raja a sacred elephant whose death in 1988 plunged sri 
lanka into mourning 
the grand old elephant who after 4000 worth of taxidermy work 
looked more robust than in his last years of life stood 
majestically inside the budhhist temple with two strings of white 
flowers hanging from his tusks 
hundreds of devotees mingled with saffronrobed monks for the 
unveiling by prime minister dingiri banda wijetunga 
raja whose name means king in the sinhalese language was 
declared a national treasure by former president junius r 
jayewardene 
for 50 years before dying at age 82 raja was the center of 
attention in kandys buddhist annual pageant which runs for two 
weeks in late july and early august 
the pageant which started in 1775 transforms the central hill 
town into a maelstrom of color light and human confusion 
intermingled with the solemnity of ancient religious rituals 
the focus of the pageant is a tooth revered by believers as a 
physical relic of the lord buddha according to legend the tooth 
was smuggled into sri lanka in the 4th century ad for safekeeping 
during the siege of dantapura capital of the ancient indian 
kingdom of kalinga 
the relic often called sri lankas most prized posession is 
kept in the temple of the tooth in kandy 55 miles northeast of 
colombo 
once a year during the pageant it is placed in a golden casket 
and paraded around the town on the back of the temples premier 
pachyderm his tusks sheathed in gold and jewels white cloth is 
spread on the streets of kandy and the procession includes two 
lesser elephants each carrying an attendant to throw sweetscented 
jasmine flowers over the precious casket 
rajas successor is an elephant named indiraja the king from 
india a present from the government of india where the 
buddhist faith began 
barely 24 hours after raja died his skin was removed and 
preserved coconut fiber plaster of paris cardboard and glue were 
used to recreate his original size and shape said thelma 
gunawardana director of the department of national museums 
it was a gigantic task mrs gunawardana said it took 
four months for a fivemember team to taxidermize the 9foot tall 
11foot long elephant 
in the room with raja were photographs from his heyday and a 
replica of the golden casket 
raja will remain on display in a building next to the temple of 
the tooth 
if we continue to take care of the elephant we could preserve 
it for a century or even more mrs gunawardana said 
