<TEXT>
foreign ministers from two dozen 
western nations gathered tuesday for a conference designed to give 
a fresh push to efforts to help the struggling economies of poland 
and hungary 
the meeting wednesday at the 18th century palais degmont will 
mark the first time the ministers have met to discuss the aid 
package 
during a paris summit in july president bush and leaders of 
other rich nations called for an aid program to speed up the drive 
for more open political systems and marketoriented economies in 
poland and hungary 
they put the european community the 12nation trading bloc in 
charge of coordinating the help 
nico wegter a spokesman for the european community said the 
main purpose of wednesdays meeting is to give sufficient 
political momentum to followup the paris summit 
secretary of state james a baker iii in europe visiting 
british and german officials will attend the conference as will 
foreign ministers joe clark of canada and taro nakayama of japan 
foreign ministers krzysztof skubiszewski of poland and gyula horn 
of hungary will address the session 
to date officials say the nations dubbed the group of 24 have 
pledged roughly 4 billion to 6 billion in a wide range of 
financial aid including loans emergency food shipments and export 
credit guarantees 
baker said in a speech to the berlin press club that the united 
states has authorized nearly 1 billion in assistance to the two 
countries 
poland and hungary have 40 years of economic stagnation to 
overcome and this will take time and our steady support he said 
in tokyo the japan broadcasting corp said the government will 
contribute 150 million to an economic stabilization fund for 
poland poland has asked for one billion dollars in that pot 
the ministers were considered likely to discuss whether they 
should expand the aid program to cover some of the other emerging 
democracies in the east 
baker said that as reforms in czechoslovakia bulgaria and east 
germany match those of poland and hungary we believe the 
activities of the group of 24 centered around the ec should be 
expanded to support peaceful change in these countries as well 
jacques delors president of the european commission the 
communitys executive body said my personal view is that this 
operation should be extended as soon as circumstances permit to 
east germany and czechoslovakia 
michel camdessus head of the international monetary fund said 
during a visit monday to warsaw that a letter of intent for a 700 
million loan agreement with poland could be initialed this week 
the deal would signal polands intention to adopt tough economic 
measures and open the way for additional loans from the world bank 
and help in stretching out the countrys 40 billion foreign debt 
hungary which has been in the forefront of economic reforms in 
the east has a foreign debt of 20 billion the highest percapita 
in eastern europe 
it also is negotiating an aid package with the imf government 
officials are planning to put forward a crisis budget of 
belttightening measures 
