<TEXT>
thousands of people who work for small 
companies are being cheated of insurance coverage by bogus plans 
sanctioned under federal law but living in a regulatory nevernever 
land witnesses told a house subcommittee tuesday 
both employers and employees are victims of the operators of the 
plans formally known as multiple employer welfare arrangements 
or less formally as health insurance arrangements the labor 
departments acting inspector general raymond maria testified 
within the benefit plan arena we are experiencing what i would 
describe as a proliferation of multiple employer welfare 
arrangements known by many names but i call them fraudulent 
trusts he said 
maria told the government operations committees subcommittee on 
legislation and national security that the plans were permitted to 
fill the vacuum left by the refusal of large insurance companies to 
provide coverage for small employers 
this vacuum is being filled by a number of fraudulent 
trusts he said in one state alone 3000 participants have 
become victims of fraud and are being held personally liable for 
more than 3 million in medical costs he said 
about 5 million such trusts exist he said the operators of the 
fraudulent ones sell their premiums at 20 percent to 50 percent 
below the rates offered by legitimate operators and the proceeds 
are embezzled often through the payment to a backup insurer that 
is really a shell company on a caribbean island he said 
these operations are not licensed by state insurance regulators 
who have reserve requirements and the outlaw plans do not maintain 
reserves to pay claims the operations run a typical pyramid game 
in which claims are drawn out and lawyers are changed he said 
when the state tries to crack down on the operators they claim 
that the federal government has jurisdiction said maria and 
patricia donovan petersen deputy insurance commissioner for 
washington state 
ms petersen told the subcommittee that she was constantly 
frustrated in her efforts to get federal help even with 
information in her 1988 investigation of two operators she said 
there wasnt even a list of companies 
one ran programs known as the western business association 
western timber association and western alliance of agriculture and 
one ran a program known as the northwest loggers association 
