<TEXT>
two mexican drug lords were sentenced tuesday 
to 40 years in prison each for the murder of us narcotics agent 
enrique camarena ending a case that had dampened relations between 
the countries since 1985 
there is no chance of these sentences being reduced 
attorney general enrique alvarez del castillo said 
rafael caro quintero 37 and ernesto rafael fonesca carrillo 
56 were found guilty of masterminding the killings of camarena an 
agent of the us drug enforcement administration and his mexican 
pilot alvarez said 
they were tried earlier this year but convictions and sentences 
are announced simultaneously in mexico 
time for related convictions of kidnapping drug trafficking and 
weapons smuggling brought caro quinteros total sentence to 116 
years and fonsecas to 144 the sentences are to be served 
concurrently 
fernando arias a spokesman for alvarez said caro quintero and 
fonseca would have to serve 74 and 53 years respectively because of 
nonconcurrent time remaining from previous sentences 
he said there is no parole in drugrelated cases not even by 
a single day 
don hamilton spokesman for us drug control policy director 
william j bennett said in washington its certainly nice to 
see people like caro quintero off the streets i think the united 
states and mexico will both be the better for it 
ten other men were sentenced to the maximum term of 40 years for 
taking part in the killings and 13 other men received lesser 
sentences for their involvement in drug operations run by caro 
quintero and fonseca 
all property and possessions of the two are being confiscated as 
part of the penalty alvarez said he had no figures for their 
holdings but said the list is very long 
both are known to have millions of dollars in assets including 
ranches aircraft luxury cars houses apartments hotels and 
businesses 
tuesdays sentences were handed down by judge tomas hernandez 
franco of the 4th criminal court in guadalajara where camarena was 
based it is the capital of jalisco state 350 miles west of mexico 
city and a major center for the drug traffickers 
alvarez the attorney general was governor of jalisco at the 
time of the camarena killing 
the slayings of camarena who was based in guadalajara and 
pilot alfredo zavala avelar and the subsequent investigation 
strained relations between mexico and the united states 
us officials said mexican authorities allowed caro quintero to 
escape to costa rica where he finally was captured in an effort 
to pressure the mexican government for action us customs 
virtually blocked the border by conducting full searches of all 
mexicans trying to enter the united states 
president carlos salinas de gortari who took office a year has 
made vigorous efforts to change mexicos image as a haven for drug 
dealers and corruption by jailing traffickers and arresting corrupt 
officials 
caro quintero worked with colombias cocaine cartels to smuggle 
drugs to the united states through mexico his story and the 
camarena killing were the subject of a book and television movie in 
the united states both called desperados 
he was sentenced to 34 years in another drug case earlier this 
year and fonseca was given 13 years arias said those will run 
consecutively with the camarena sentences 
it was revealed in july that caro quintero and fonseca had 
bribed mexico city prison officials to allow them to live in luxury 
accomodations they had built inside the prison 
camarena was kidnapped feb 7 1985 in guadalajara and zavala 
avelar a few days later their bulletriddled bodies showing signs 
of torture were found march 5 on a ranch 60 miles southeast of 
guadalajara 
the bodies wrapped in plastic bags had been buried in shallow 
graves 
in a related case ruben zuno arce 59 was arraigned monday in 
a los angeles court on charges of conspiracy in the camarena 
killing 
zuno arce a brotherinlaw of former president luis echeverria 
is among 13 people in the united states charged in connection with 
the drug agents death 
alvarez said the mexican government had no evidence against zuno 
arce and there was no connection to tuesdays sentencing 
