<TEXT>
murder and torture continue in the war zones of 
sudan despite the change of governments amnesty international said 
in a report released tuesday 
the human rights group said soldiers killed 34 civilian 
detainees in the southern garrison town of wau on july 19 three 
weeks after the military took power in a coup 
it is believed that the armed forces have done nothing to 
punish those responsible for these unlawful killings the report 
said the military governments apparent lack of response to the 
killings in wau and its continuing detention of political opponents 
in the north of sudan is a cause for grave human rights concern 
londonbased amnesty international said prisoners held by the 
military have been tortured to force confessions 
a wellreported instance of cruel tying on 10 march 1989 in 
the south kordofan town of meiram caused the death of one man and 
led to the eventual amputation of the arms of two others the 
report said similar cases are known from the towns of delami 
addamazin chali and juba 
it said there were reports of some victims having their wrists 
and elbows tied behind their backs and others had their ankles 
bound to their wrists and then left face down 
gross abuses also have been carried out by militias supplied and 
supported by the armed forces and successive sudanese governments 
according to the report it said some of the most serious abuses 
have involved militias formed among the nomadic rizeiqat and 
misseriya peoples of south darfur and south kordofan 
successive administrations including the current military 
government have failed to act forthrightly against deliberate 
killings and torture in and around areas of armed conflict the 
report said 
since the outbreak of war in 1983 there have been few official 
investigations into human rights violations and as far as amnesty 
international is aware no prosecutions for unlawful killings or 
torture this amounts to a willful failure by the sudan government 
to protect basic human rights 
the organization said human rights also are violated by the 
rebels sudan peoples liberation army 
the spla has extrajudicially executed prisoners such as 
government troops and militia captured in combat suspected 
government informers and civilians thought to be opposed to the 
spla the report said it is believed that some hundreds of 
captured government troops were killed in bor in march 1989 there 
are also reports of extrajudicial executions of civilians by the 
spla in south kordofan and equatoria 
