<TEXT>
a house panel began an investigation tuesday 
of apparently contradictory methods used by the nuclear 
regulatory commission in deciding whether to allow the seabrook 
nuclear plant to open 
rep peter kostmeyer dpa chairman of the house interior 
committee oversight and investigations subcommittee demanded 
answers from nrc chairman kenneth carr on nrc procedure 
this inquiry has been prompted by the steady erosion of safety 
standards enacted by congress following the major nuclear accident 
at three mile island in pennsylvania and by the extraordinary 
series of apparently contradictory actions recently taken by the 
commission and its licensing board concerning the application for a 
fullpower operating license at seabrook station in new 
hampshire kostmeyer said in a letter to carr 
nrc spokesman frank ingram said the letter had not been 
received but would be responded to promptly 
the commission is following its usual license procedures on 
seabrook ingram said 
legislators from around new england called for the investigation 
last month after the nrcs atomic safety and licensing board 
recommended that seabrook should be awarded a license 
kostmeyer cited a recent dispute in which the licensing board 
downplayed concerns raised by the nrcs higher level atomic safety 
and licensing appeal board about the adequacy of new hampshire 
evacuation plans 
it is apparent that the commission is dangerously close to 
twisting the intent of congress to a point where it can no longer 
be said that the public health and safety protection afforded by 
one emergency plan is equivalent to another kostmeyer wrote 
kostmeyer was particularly concerned that the licensing board 
issued a final decision on massachusetts evacuation plans only two 
days after the appeal board raised its concerns about the new 
hampshire plans 
the letter to carr included 11 questions about nrc procedure and 
requested answers no later than dec 20 among other things 
kostmeyer asked whether the geographic location of a plant and the 
relative difficulty of evacuating residents from that area was 
relevant in licensing a plant 
mike connolly an aide to us rep edward markey dmass said 
there was no immediate word on how soon the oversight committee 
would begin hearings 
in a related development the licensing board dismissed a 
complaint tuesday about the adequacy of an emergency drill at the 
seabrook plant and said the massachusetts attorney general filed 
his concerns too late 
ron sher spokesman for new hampshire yankee electric co the 
operater of the plant for the multicompany owning consortium 
said seabrook station has been the most closely scrutinized 
nuclear plant ever licenses and the in the 18year licensing 
history of seabrook intervenors have had ample opportunity to make 
their case 
sher said experts had found the emergency plan one of the best 
in the country 
