<TEXT>
many of the 27 children and adults killed 
in a fiery bus crash could have survived if their seats had been 
fire resistant and the buss fuel tank had been improved defense 
witnesses testified tuesday 
safety issues dominated the 13th day of testimony in the murder 
and drunkendriving trial of larry mahoney driver of the pickup 
truck that collided headon with the church bus south of this ohio 
river town on may 14 1988 
eugene sober a fire safety engineer with the national 
aeronautics and space administration said the 1977 ford bus seat 
cushions and covers burn rapidly and emit toxic smoke that kill 
passengers within minutes 
thomas feaheny a former ford motor co vice president 
testified that existing technology could have prevented the fire 
but was not allowed to give any details 
feaheny also testified that a protective cage around the bus 
gasoline tank probably would not have prevented the blaze 
carroll circuit judge charles satterwhite has ruled that any 
information about technology that could have prevented the bus fire 
is inadmissable in the trial 
anytime there is evidence that has been excluded obviously it 
hurts us defense attorney russell baldani said in an afternoon 
press conference 
sobers testimony dealt with the deadly effects of flexible 
polyurethane foam the material in the cushions and 
polychlorinated vinyl the plastic seat covering 
flexible polyurethane foam is the single largest class of 
fuels involved with fatal fires sober said 
when burned untreated foam emits hydrogen cyanide gas and the 
plastic emits hydrogen chloride gas he said in addition the fire 
produces carbon monoxide gas forcing people to breathe harder and 
faster 
sober said the fire hazards of the material used for the seats 
were well known in the early 1970s 
foam treated with fire retardant was readily available to the 
automotive industry when the school bus later sold to the radcliff 
first assembly of god church as surplus was manufactured in 1977 
he said 
seats treated with fire retardant would have saved lives in the 
crash he said there would have certainly been a lot more time 
for them to escape sober said 
feaheny a 26year ford employee said the crash was the worst 
single tragedy i ever heard of in the industry and it could have 
been prevented 
he said a fire beneath the bus boiled gasoline in the metal fuel 
tank like a teakettle and squirted flaming gasoline into the 
bus like a flame thrower 
under crossexamination feaheny said that while he never had 
any direct involvement in the design and development of buses at 
ford his overall experience in the mechanical systems of trucks 
and cars provided him the basis to discuss the fuel tank safety of 
the 1977 ford bus 
feaheny fired in september 1983 had sued six ford executives 
for about 30 million in damages alleging they interfered with his 
career development a verdict in the suit went against feaheny in 
december 1986 and is on appeal 
baldani asked feaheny if he had an ax to grind with ford 
feaheny said he did not 
