<DOCNO> AP891212-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
domestic advertising spending should grow 
slightly faster in 1990 than it did in 1989 and should improve 
further through the next decade a prominent media forecaster says 
robert j coen who heads the forecasting unit at the 
advertising agency mccannerickson said in his semiannual 
projection monday that ad spending will rise 62 percent next year 
to 1326 billion following 58 percent growth in 1989 
the outlook for the opening year of the decade is rather 
modest but the pace of ad growth can be expected to improve as the 
decade unfolds he said 
coens estimate included projected increases of 63 percent in 
national ad spending to 7385 billion next year and 62 percent 
in local ad spending to 5879 billion 
national ad spending rose 59 percent this year while local ad 
spending was up 55 percent he said 
a year ago coen projected a 61 percent spending increase for 
1989 and boosted that estimate last summer to 69 percent 
he said ad spending came in below both projections because of 
slowerthanexpected growth in direct mail advertising due to a 
postal rate increase 
advertising overseas is expected to rise 5 percent to 1337 
billion next year matching its 1989 rise coen said 
his remarks came at the start of a weeklong media conference for 
securities analysts conducted for the 17th year by the investment 
firm painewebber inc 
coen said economists expect the us gross national product will 
grow 58 percent in 1990 including inflation down from 72 percent 
in 1989 
but coen said he saw signs indicating the ad outlook is 
improving despite the weakening economy stronger than expected 
growth in ad spending in the mass consumer media such as radio 
television magazines and newspapers in 1989 and healthy growth in 
key ad categories such as automobiles restaurants liquor and 
computers 
he said national advertisers are expected to make their biggest 
ad spending increases in the broadcast media a 69 percent jump in 
1990 
cable tv and syndicated tv will have doubledigit growth again 
although below their 30 percent and 35 percent increases of 1989 
coen said while radio will be up but at a slower pace 
he said the three major tv networks also will have an increase 
of unspecified proportions compared with almost no growth in ad 
revenue in 1989 
in a separate appearance david f poltrack senior vice 
president for planning and research at cbs broadcast group said he 
expected a combined 8 percent to 9 percent rise in revenues for 
cbs abc and nbc next year and compound annual growth of 75 
percent through 1995 
coen said national print advertising will rise 66 percent with 
magazine growth moderating and spending in newspapers remaining 
soft 
local newspaper advertising spending is expected to rise 60 
percent held back to some extent by very soft demand for 
classified advertising coen said local advertising on broadcast 
media is expected to rise 66 percent with a stimulus from 
congressional campaign ads 
in a separate panel discussion of the outlook for newspapers in 
1990 jerome s tilis a marketing executive for knightridder 
newspaper sales said he expects a 5 percent increase in overall 
newspaper ad revenue in 1990 compared with estimated growth of 5 
percent to 6 percent this year 
he said he expects turmoil caused by takeovers in the retailing 
business will settle down and help retail advertising in 
newspapers and that gains in real estate and automotive classified 
advertising will help offset a drop in helpwanted ads 
tilis said newspapers should benefit from price increases for 
direct mail advertising continuing fragmentation of the network tv 
audience and development of newspaper networks such as the one that 
resulted in creation of an advertising island in the middle of 
the stock listings in some papers 
