<DOCNO> AP891212-0208 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
frances last remaining currency controls will be 
lifted on jan 1 1990 the finance ministry announced tuesday 
the widely anticipated move will allow french residents to hold 
foreign currency accounts inside the country and open bank accounts 
outside france 
under a timetable set up by the european community france and 
most other common market countries have until july 1 1990 to lift 
their controls on capital movement spain portugal and greece have 
until jan 1 1993 
the bulk of frances currency controls covering major capital 
movement by corporations were dismantled gradually in a series of 
steps that began in 1984 
the ministry said in a statement the lifting of the controls 
reflects government confidence in the good health of the french 
economy and in the stability of our currency 
the move also underlines our desire to accelerate progress 
toward european monetary union the statement said 
a ministry spokeswoman confirmed that french residents will be 
obliged to notify authorities when they open foreign bank accounts 
as they must do for accounts opened in france 
currency traders said the announcement did not have any 
immediate impact on the foreign exchange market they said the lack 
of response reflected the relatively limited scope of the remaining 
controls and the markets knowledge that they were already 
scheduled to come down by july 1 1990 at the latest 
the decision by france to lift its exchange controls removes one 
of the obstacles frequently cited by british prime minister 
margaret thatcher that has prevented britain from seeking full 
membership for its currency in the european monetary system 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

