<TEXT>
rapidly growing imports pushed japans trade 
surplus sharply lower in november its seventh consecutive monthly 
decline from yearearlier levels the finance ministry announced 
tuesday 
the trade surplus calculated on a customsclearance basis 
shrank 462 percent to 353 billion from a year earlier when it 
registered 656 billion dollars the ministry said the surplus 
also fell from octobers 465 billion 
exports dropped 29 percent from their yearearlier level to 
2203 billion while imports climbed 148 percent to 1850 
billion the ministry said 
the trade surplus latest decline from yearearlier levels was 
the largest since october 1982 when it fell 541 percent 
japans surplus with the united states declined from 
yearearlier levels for the second consecutive month falling 193 
percent to 357 billion 
imports from the united states buoyed by increased purchases of 
aircraft office equipment and nonferrous metals grew 121 percent 
to 408 billion exports to the united states dropped 52 percent 
to 765 billion largely because of falling auto shipments 
ministry officials said 
ministry officials attributed the decline in the overall surplus 
mainly to growing imports of crude oil both in value and volume 
terms because of rising world oil prices the average price of oil 
jumped 383 percent from a year earlier to 1741 a barrel while 
volume increased by 129 percent to 49 billion gallons they said 
imports of manufactured goods also rose 13 percent from the 
previous year and accounted for 506 percent of overall imports 
they said it was the sixth month in a row that manufactured goods 
exceeded 50 percent of total imports 
in contrast exports of motor vehicles fell 94 percent because 
of sluggish demand and rising production by japanese manufacturers 
in north america they said steel exports fell 236 percent 
because of weak worldwide sales the officials added 
compared to their october levels exports declined 44 percent 
and imports rose 07 percent the ministry said 
although japans trade surplus a target of sharp criticism from 
the united states and other trading partners has fallen for seven 
months in a row ministry officials said they were not sure whether 
the decline was permanent 
we have to see what the future will bring said an official 
in charge of trade data a lot of things will depend on how oil 
prices will change and there are other elements of uncertainty 
after seasonal factors were taken into account the november 
trade surplus came to 470 billion up from 377 billion the 
previous month 
japan calculates its trade surplus figures on a 
customsclearance basis in which freight and insurance costs are 
included in import figures but not in exports 
</TEXT>
