general says a study financed by the organization that runs the 
overthecounter stock market 
two researchers at the state university of new york at stony 
brook professor glenn yago and assistant jeff yanenbaum compared 
the performance of 426 companies making initial public offerings 
ipos from 1943 to 1985 with companies in their industry as well 
as industry averages 
we found that going public tends to have a profound effect on 
corporate performance said the studys authors who are with 
stony brooks w averell harriman school for managament and policy 
the study funded and released monday by the washingtonbased 
national association of securities dealers compared the 
performance of companies making ipos and their respective industry 
in several key areas employment revenues sales per employee 
capital investment capital spending working capital net fixed 
assets and total assets 
but because of certain data limitations information on some 
of our variables was not available for all ipos in our study the 
28page study explained in its methodology section 
still we were able to examine at least 268 ipos for each 
variable and in some cases considerably more it continued 
in each of th areas we examined ipo firms outpaced their 
industries by a considerable margin yago and tanenbaum said 
in a period when corporate industry as a whole was losing jobs 
the ipo firms showed substantial employment gains in other 
variables we examined ipo firms grew from 25 to nearly 17 times 
