<TEXT>
a lawsuit accusing the julien co of 
failing to meet a 435 million margin call on the new york cotton 
exchange claims the leading cotton merchant is in financial trouble 
julien hohenberg founder and president of the memphis company 
was unavailable for comment tuesday at his office or residence 
the lawsuit filed monday by painwebber inc says the julien 
co failed to meet the margin call on dec 8 one day after a 
similar call for 2 million 
painewebber said it froze the julien cos account but was left 
with a shortfall of 23 million 
the lawsuit follows last weeks sharp drop in cotton prices and 
market observers say that may have been partly caused by a major 
merchant selling holdings to meet a margin call 
until this past week the julien co has always been very 
prompt in satisfying margin calls said the lawsuit filed in 
shelby county chancery court 
brokers often allow a customer to trade on credit but if prices 
fall below the customers collateral he can be asked to meet that 
margin by coming up with additional money 
the shelby county court issued orders barring the julien co 
from disposing of its assets other than what is necessary in the 
ordinary course of business 
painewebber alleges upon information and belief that the 
julien co has recently incurred other substantial liabilities in 
addition to its liabilities to painewebber the lawsuit says 
industry observers say cotton prices have been low even though 
the nations cotton surplus is relatively small cutbacks in 
purchases by textile mills and a large domestic cotton crop this 
year may have attributed to that market sluggishness the observers 
say 
the julien co is a leading cotton merchant memphis has been a 
center of cotton trade since mississippi river paddlewheelers 
brought in cotton from plantations throughout the delta and julien 
hohenbergs family has been in the business since 1879 
his familys business hohenberg bros was sold to cargill 
inc in 1975 and became that companys cotton subsidiary 
hohenberg who had been president of the family business since 
1961 continued to run hohenberg bros until 1985 when he retired 
and formed the julien co 
